''Hadropithecus'' is an [[extinct]] genus of [[lemur]], or [[strepsirrhine]] [[primate]], that includes a single species, ''Hadropithecus stenognathus''.  According to [[Linnaean taxonomy]], it belongs to the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Archaeolemuridae]], which in turn belongs to the infraorder [[Lemuriformes]], which includes all the Malagasy lemurs.<ref name="Nowak" />

Originally thought to have been a sister group to the living [[indri]]ds and the recently extinct [[sloth lemur]]s (family Palaeopropithecidae) because of similarities in their skull and teeth,<ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd">{{cite book | last1 = Mittermeier | first1 = R. A. | last2 = Tattersall | first2 = I. | last3 = Konstant | first3 = W.R. | last4 = Meyers | first4 = D.M. | last5 = Mast | first5 = R.B. | authorlink1 = Russell Mittermeier | authorlink2 = Ian Tattersall | others = Illustrated by S.D. Nash | title = Lemurs of Madagascar | chapter = Chapter 4: The Extinct Lemurs | pages = 33<U+2013>48 | edition = 1st | publisher = Conservation International | year = 1994 | isbn = 1-881173-08-9}}</ref><ref name="NaturalChange6">{{cite book | editor1-last = Goodman | editor1-first = SM | editor2-last = Patterson | editor2-first = BD | last1 = Simons | first1 = EL | chapter = Chapter 6: Lemurs: Old and New | title = Natural Change and Human Impact in Madagascar | pages = 142<U+2013>166 | publisher = Smithsonian Institution Press | year = 1997 | isbn = 978-1560986829}}</ref> there was some debate over whether the monkey lemurs (''Hadropithecus'' and ''Archaeolemur'') or the sloth lemurs were more closely related to today's indrids.  The monkey lemurs had skulls that more closely resembled the indrids, but their teeth were very specialized and unlike those of the indrids.  The sloth lemurs, on the other hand, had teeth like the indrids, but very specialized skulls.  The matter was settled with the discovery of new skeletons of ''[[Babakotia]]'' and ''[[Mesopropithecus]]'', two genera of sloth lemur, both of which had indrid-like skulls and teeth.<ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd" />  More recently, there had been some debate over whether or not the monkey lemurs were more closely related to the [[Lemuridae|lemurid]]s based [[postcrania]]l traits and other features shown in [[subfossil]] remains found in the first half of the 2000s .<ref name="2006Godfrey">{{cite journal | last1 = Godfrey | first1 = LR | last2 = Jungers | first2 = WL | last3 = Burney | first3 = DA | last4 = Vasey | first4 = N | last5 = Ramilisonina | last6 = Wheeler | first6 = W | last7 = Lemelin | first7 = P | last8 = Shapiro | first8 = LJ | last9 = Schwartz | first9 = GT | last10 = King | first10 = SJ | last11 = Ramarolahy | first11 = MF | last12 = Raharivony | first12 = LL | last13 = Randria | first13 = GF | title = New discoveries of skeletal elements of ''Hadropithecus stenognathus'' from Andrahomana Cave, southeastern Madagascar | journal = Journal of Human Evolution | year = 2006 | volume = 51 | issue = 4 | pages = 395<U+2013>410 | doi = 10.1016/j.jhevol.2006.04.012}}</ref>  However, [[DNA sequencing]] has reaffirmed the sister group status of the monkey lemurs to indrids and sloth lemurs.<ref name="2008Orlando" />

