==Anatomy and physiology==
''Hadropithecus stenognathus'' has been estimated to have weighed between {{convert|27|and|35|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and to be roughly the same size as ''Archaeolemur'', although more gracile.<ref name="Nowak" /><ref name="Mittermeier_2ndEd" />  Newer subfossil finds, however, suggest that ''Hadropithecus'' may have been more robust, and more like a [[gorilla]] than a baboon.<ref name="Lemurs3" />  Both lemurs were [[Quadrupedalism|quadrupedal]] (walked on four legs).<ref name="Mittermeier_2ndEd" />  There is no evidence of [[cursorial]]ity (adaptations specifically for running) in either species.<ref name="Lemurs3">{{cite book | editor1-last = Gould | editor1-first = L | editor2-last = Sauther | editor2-first = ML | last1 = Godfrey | first1 = LR | last2 = Jungers | first2 = WL | last3 = Schwartz | first3 = GT | chapter = Chapter 3: Ecology and Extinction of Madagascar's Subfossil Lemurs | title = Lemurs: Ecology and Adaptation | pages = 41<U+2013>64 | publisher = Springer | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-0387-34585-7}}</ref>

Although fewer post-cranial remains have been discovered for ''Hadropithecus'' compared to ''Archaeolemur'', what has been found indicates that both were adapted for a [[Terrestrial animal|terrestrial]] lifestyle, with short limbs and a powerful build.<ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd" />  Due to its specialized dentition and likely diet, ''Hadropithecus'' is thought to have been the more terrestrial of the two.<ref name="NaturalChange6" />  Both genera also have shortened hands and feet that have been described as almost "paw-like."<ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd" />  ''Hadropithecus'' had shorter [[metatarsal]]s and limbs, as well as a broader thorax.  Its [[phalange]]s were also more curved than those of baboons.<ref name="NaturalChange8" />

<!-- Note to Visionholder: Return to Walker's Mammals of the World and page 247 in Natural Change for more details on dentition -->
The face of ''Hadropithecus'' was shortened and adapted to heavy stress from chewing.  The monkey lemurs were known for their highly specialized teeth, but ''Hadropithecus'' went further by specializing in strong grinding.<ref name="NaturalChange8">{{cite book | editor1-last = Goodman | editor1-first = SM | editor2-last = Patterson | editor2-first = BD | last1 = Simons | last1 = Godfrey | first1 = LR | last2 = Jungers | first2 = WL | last3 = Reed | first3 = KE | last4 = Simons | first4 = EL | last5 = Chatrath | first5 = PS | chapter = Chapter 8: Subfossil Lemurs | title = Natural Change and Human Impact in Madagascar | pages = 218<U+2013>256 | publisher = Smithsonian Institution Press | year = 1997 | isbn = 978-1560986829}}</ref>  It had expanded [[Molar (tooth)|molar]]s that wore down quickly,<ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd" /> much like those of [[ungulate]]s,<ref name="Nowak" /> and its posterior [[premolars]] acted like molars to extend the grinding surface.<ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd" />  It also had a robust [[mandible]] to facilitate crushing hard objects.<ref name="NaturalChange8" />  Even the [[incisors]] and strepsirrhine [[toothcomb]] were reduced in this species.<ref name="Nowak" /><ref name="Sussman4" /><ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd" />  Its [[dental formula]] was: {{DentalFormula|upper=2.1.3.3|lower=1.1.3.3|total=34}}<ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd" />

==Ecology==
Like all other lemurs, ''Hadropithecus'' was [[Endemism|endemic]] to Madagascar.  Because it died out only recently and is only known from subfossil remains, it is considered to be a modern form of Malagasy lemur.<ref name="Sussman4" />  Formerly found only in the Central Plateau, South, and Southwest regions, it is thought to have been terrestrial or semi-terrestrial, an unusual trait for lemurs.<ref name="Nowak" /><ref name="Mittermeier_2ndEd" /><ref name="Sussman4" /><ref name="NaturalChange6" />  Within its original range, there were few other lemurs to overlap its [[ecological niche]], and it has been shown to be the only subfossil lemur to consume both [[C3 carbon fixation|C3]] and [[C4 carbon fixation|C4]] (or [[CAM photosynthesis|CAM]]) plants, an indication that it lived in more open habitats and had a varied diet.<ref name="Mittermeier_2ndEd" /><ref name="Lemurs3" />  Its physiology and [[dentition]] suggest that it was a lot like the [[Gelada|Gelada Baboon]] in locomotion and diet.<ref name="Nowak" /><ref name="Sussman4" /><ref name="Mittermeier_1stEd" />  It was probably a [[Grazing|manual grazer]] and its teeth were well-adapted for grinding either grass or seeds.<ref name="Sussman4" /><ref name="NaturalChange6" />  Microwear patterns on its teeth, as well as its overly large molars, indicate it processed hard objects like nuts or seeds, making it a [[Seed predation|seed predator]].<ref name="Lemurs3" /><ref name="NaturalChange8" />

==Extinction==
Already considered a rare species due to the low number of subfossil finds,<ref name="NaturalChange6" /> ''Hadropithecus'' died out sooner than its sister taxon, ''Archaeolemur''.<ref name="Mittermeier_2ndEd" />  Both species disappeared shortly after the arrival of humans to the island, but being a large, specialized, terrestrial grazer, it would have faced more pressure from domestic [[livestock]], introduced [[pigs]], and spreading human populations than its more generalized cousin.<ref name="Nowak" />  It disappeared completely from Madagascar around 444<U+2013>772 [[Common Era|CE]].<ref name="Mittermeier_2ndEd" />

